Because $\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta = 1, $$\sin^6 \theta + \cos^6 \theta = (\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta) (\sin^4 \theta – \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta + \cos^4 \theta)$$\\ 
Since $\sin 2 \theta = 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta = \frac{1}{3}$, $\sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta = \frac{1}{36}.$$\\ 
Let’s write $(\sin^4 \theta + \cos^4 \theta)$:$$
\begin{align} &\sin^4 \theta + \cos^4 \theta = (\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta)^2 – 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta = 1 – \frac{1}{3} = \frac{2}{3} \\
& \sin^4 \theta + \cos^4 \theta = (\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta)^2 – 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta = 1 – \frac{1}{3} = \frac{2}{3}
\end{align} 
$$
  Substitute these results into $\sin^4 \theta – \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta + \cos^4 \theta$, we get the final answer:$$
\sin^6 \theta + \cos^6 \theta = (\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta) (\sin^4 \theta – \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta + \cos^4 \theta)$$
$$
\begin{align}
\sin^6 \theta + \cos^6 \theta &= (\frac{2}{3} – \frac{1}{36}) + 1 \\
&= 1 + \frac{48}{36} – \frac{1}{36} \\
&= \frac{97}{36}
\end{align}
